  "eprint": {
    "title": "More Efficient Amortization of Exact Zero-Knowledge Proofs for LWE",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Jonathan Bootle",
        "email": "jbt@zurich",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Vadim Lyubashevsky",
        "email": "comvad@zurich",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Ngoc Khanh Nguyen",
        "email": "comnkn@zurich",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Gregor Seiler",
        "email": "comgseiler@inf",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We propose a practical zero-knowledge proof system for proving knowledge of\nshort solutions s, e to linear relations A s + e= u mod q which gives the most\nefficient solution for two naturally-occurring classes of problems.  The first\nis when A is very ``tall'', which corresponds to a large number of LWE\ninstances that use the same secret s.  In this case, we show that the proof\nsize is independent of the height of the matrix (and thus the length of the\nerror vector e) and rather only linearly depends on the length of s.  The\nsecond case is when A is of the form A' tensor I, which corresponds to proving\nmany LWE instances (with different secrets) that use the same samples A'.  The\nlength of this second proof is square root in the length of s, which\ncorresponds to square root of the length of all the secrets.  Our\nconstructions combine recent advances in ``purely'' lattice-based\nzero-knowledge proofs with the Reed-Solomon proximity testing ideas present in\nsome generic zero-knowledge proof systems -- with the main difference is that\nthe latter are applied directly to the lattice instances without going through\nintermediate problems.",
    "keywords": [
      "Lattices",
      "Zero-Knowledge Proofs",
      "LWE",
      "Amortization"
    ],
